ADR-04: Use a Separate Model for Maintenance History Tracking

Status  
Accepted

Context  
The remote housing crisis application must not only store repair requests, but also track the progress and history of maintenance actions taken over time.

A simple design option would be to store only one current status field inside the `RepairRequest` model. However, this approach would overwrite previous updates and make it difficult to preserve a maintenance history for each repair issue.

Because the system requirement includes repair tracking and maintenance history, a design decision was needed on how to represent ongoing repair progress in the database.

Decision  
We decided to use a separate `MaintenanceUpdate` model linked to `RepairRequest` through a `ForeignKey` relationship.

This design allows each repair request to have multiple maintenance updates, where each update stores:
- a note describing the maintenance action
- a status snapshot at that point in time
- the person or role who updated it
- the date and time of the update

This approach creates a historical record of repair progress instead of replacing previous information.

Rationale  
A separate maintenance history model was chosen because it better reflects the real-world repair workflow.

Why this approach was selected:
- A repair issue may go through multiple stages such as reported, in progress, on hold, and completed
- Each stage may involve different notes or actions
- Historical updates must be preserved for tracking and accountability
- The design supports future features such as audit trails, reporting, and progress timelines

This approach also aligns with object-oriented design by giving maintenance history its own responsibility instead of combining all behavior into one model.

Alternatives Considered  

1. Store only one status field in `RepairRequest`
Advantages:
- Simple to implement
- Fewer models required

Disadvantages:
- Overwrites earlier progress
- No history of maintenance actions
- Difficult to audit or review repair timeline
- Does not fully support maintenance history requirement


2. Store maintenance notes as plain text inside `RepairRequest`
Advantages:
- Easy to implement
- Keeps information in one place

Disadvantages:
- Hard to structure
- Difficult to query individual updates
- Poor support for chronological repair tracking
- Mixing multiple responsibilities into one model


3. Use a separate `MaintenanceUpdate` model
Advantages:
- Preserves historical repair progress
- Supports one-to-many relationship with repair requests
- Easier to query and manage updates
- Better object-oriented decomposition
- Supports future extension

Disadvantages:
- Slightly more complex data model
- Requires additional relationship handling


Consequences  

Positive:
- Enables full maintenance history tracking
- Avoids loss of past repair information
- Improves auditability and accountability
- Supports future reporting and timeline views
- Reflects real-world repair workflow more accurately

Negative:
- Increases number of models in the system
- Requires additional joins when retrieving repair history


Code Reference  
- `housing/models.py`  
  - `RepairRequest` model  
  - `MaintenanceUpdate` model  
  - `ForeignKey` relationship between `MaintenanceUpdate` and `RepairRequest`


Conclusion  
Using a separate `MaintenanceUpdate` model provides a more scalable and accurate way to represent repair progress in the housing application. It supports the project requirement for maintenance history while maintaining clean object-oriented design.